Inflation, in Europe, has shifted over food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 countries of the euro area was higher than the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg reported.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the United States, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, with higher commodity prices and lower unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "It is necessary to deter inflation" so that it will no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent is a record over the past 12 years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off because of the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
Grain market shares have increased by 88 per cent and soy prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products has also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and, last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will fall from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent but in 2009, it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the master rate twice in 2008.
