Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year compared with the fact that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article of Napi Gazdaság (Day Economy)
This year, in the trade triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a significantly higher value than a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
The prices, "which had already flown away" in the large food stores last December, did not increase sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that goods purchased well below nine thousand forks last year now cost more than ten thousand forks.
The Daily Shopping Cart in the tested hypermarkets exceeded at least 91 forints, the psychological threshold of ten thousand fornts.
And the highest value in the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forks.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but the prices of turkey net, nuts and peacock bass have increased significantly.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) data but, at Auchan, there was only one kilo of bread at 139 forints.
Competition has not lowered the product price below 200 forks.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle made up of two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forks, so it only cost 257 forks the bottle recorded including.
It does not prevent that this year, in terms of Daily Shopping Cart, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of its daily Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan have increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket and the cheapest basket this year, we find a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year's lowest and most expensive basket this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forks.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forks, while aware that the impact of the increase in VAT rate was already seen in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has caused trade to be perplexed, and hypermarkets could not clearly determine how much margin to apply on products so far they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a merchant miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than 1,720 fornts at the 2006 value, whereas the difference between the least expensive baskets was only 844 fornts.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was higher than that of last year and prices at least increased by 1,284 fornts as well.
Nearing the two Christmas seasons, we found a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some essential foods, the Institute of Statistics has seen an increase in prices by more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily Cartel of the latter, this seems almost absurd, since the price level of this product, already quite expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 per cent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a higher position than egg suppliers because they have managed to make the brutal price increase accepted by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-preserved foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails formed in the boxes of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is lower in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals make the economy on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the improper use of antibiotics, were registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overhauling of medical personnel do not help block infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also make the economy on disinfectants
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed for trauma at János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured from a serious car accident came out of the hospital but soon after he had to return because of MRSA infection, and since then doctors have been unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National System of Nosocomial Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
That is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacilline-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of the people are carriers of the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as angina, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily healing.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in the poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged functioning of the immune system, this bacterium may cause serious hospital infections, such as trauma or septicemia, on the elderly, small weight or weak body.
According to hospital director János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital daily.
Above all, you should not confuse infection with the epidemic, you can't find MRSA just the one or you won't look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs resist antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff puts rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of MRSA infections may be prevented but current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It is important to know that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases only see the day if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor at the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the recovery of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The realization of microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient care and basic care, Karolina Böröcz reported.
Many hospitals make the economy on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, to put on gloves and masks of protection. However, important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferates by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemics, the patients should be kept away from each other by a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in demonstrably or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenditures for social security funds, which is why we are fighting all over this infection.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs too) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
