Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements worth EUR 400 million in Budapest on a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of the transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, whose credit contracts amounting to EUR 100 million have already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of EUR 50 million for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope first in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the draft metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would redeploy the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary has completed the details of the metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its appropriations in accordance with the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment fee.
