British Army recruits on YouTube
The British army units report on the video sharing site records made during their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with a view to becoming popular.
First of all, it was the British Air Force (RAF) who was passionate about YouTube: the special units involved in Afghanistan carry video sequences on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, announced the BBC.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the headquarters of the air force operations in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londres or the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is indisputable
Air force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and broadcasts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were posted on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make public the real objectives of the military's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertising on television, communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have played a game
The army is mad because, except for carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have passed on to the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In addition, many videos had already been broadcast on the net showing the operating areas in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only been packed for loading these videos recently.
The Americans recruit a little differently by using the America's Army shooting game for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
