A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are free access.
The 47 million archive documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were so far available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, upon request of an old victim or his entitled.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratifying this agreement by all States has been complete and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research "including on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers," says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the public's opening of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
Records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to give them proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to wait for these documents," said Mr. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Universityät Technische in Berlin in 2006.
