Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel with its parliamentary formality, which ended today with the vote by Congress of amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the objective of its entry into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the various groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the organization's activities to ensure that markets operate effectively.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, implies the modernisation of financial markets, as it strengthens investor protection, improves the powers of the leaders of the National Securities Market Commission (NCMV) and promotes cooperation among the various leaders of the European Union.
The new regulations will provide financial advisory services for both specialized social reasons and natural and legal persons and create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial consulting companies (FAIs), which merge value companies, securities agencies and portfolio managers.
In addition, it increases the number of operations systems on financial instruments, so that it can be added to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and order internationalization systems, which face competition from current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment service companies to disclose on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they perform, to facilitate control by the NCMV.
In passing through the Congressional Economics Commission, several amendments were added, one of which shows that held debts will be considered as a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which demonstrated itself with what happened with the debt of high-risk American mortgages (subprime).
