Venus is Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lights in the atmosphere and wind turbines at the poles, similar to those appearing in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightnings on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now shown evidence - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lights on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometres of cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California to Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprint, the lightnings would have revealed life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case with Venus: "If there was a life, it must have been on a very old date of history," explains Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is perhaps Earth's infernal twin, but she remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which resembles so much the earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the mission ASE.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venezuelan research, since no more probes were on the way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles do not only highlight Venus' uniqueness within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more than expected at first sight.
Thus, in addition to the wind turbines already known at the north pole, researchers found a cloud-float at the south pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, wrote a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Institute of Astrophysica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 km, almost as large.
The planet qualified as a star in the evening or in the morning revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venetian day lasts 243 territorial days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly remembers the Earth, scientists assume that both planets have formed under similar conditions.
Of the two, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost itself in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide was fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes on Venus most of the atmosphere.
